<subSubSection pageId="99" pageNumber="100" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="99.[140,1108,167,580]" pageId="99" pageNumber="100">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[185,310,237,263]" pageId="99" pageNumber="100">
<emphasis box="[185,304,237,263]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="99" pageNumber="100" reason="1">Diagnosis</emphasis>
.
</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authorityName="Crabo &amp; Lafontaine" authorityYear="2009" baseAuthorityName="Crabo &amp; Lafontaine" baseAuthorityYear="2009" box="[318,557,237,263]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Psammopolia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="99" pageNumber="100" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ochracea">
<emphasis box="[318,557,237,263]" italics="true" pageId="99" pageNumber="100">Psammopolia ochracea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is the smallest and most widely distributed Californian species. It is dark brown, often reddish, and has a large orbicular spot that is open along the radial vein. Th e conspicuous orbicular and reniform spots are outlined in black and filled with pale scales peripherally and darker ground scales centrally. The genitalia of both sexes are similar to those of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Crabo &amp; Lafontaine" authorityYear="2009" baseAuthorityName="Crabo &amp; Lafontaine" baseAuthorityYear="2009" box="[542,637,378,404]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Psammopolia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="99" pageNumber="100" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="arietis">
<emphasis box="[542,558,379,404]" italics="true" pageId="99" pageNumber="100">P</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[573,637,379,404]" italics="true" pageId="99" pageNumber="100">arietis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Th e male is the only 
<taxonomicName box="[888,1030,378,404]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Psammopolia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="99" pageNumber="100" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[888,1030,378,404]" italics="true" pageId="99" pageNumber="100">Psammopolia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
with a bipectinate antenna. Females differ from the other Californian species in the length of the corpus bursae, 1.75× the ductus bursae in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Crabo &amp; Lafontaine" authorityYear="2009" baseAuthorityName="Crabo &amp; Lafontaine" baseAuthorityYear="2009" box="[647,766,448,475]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Psammopolia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="99" pageNumber="100" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ochracea">
<emphasis box="[647,663,449,474]" italics="true" pageId="99" pageNumber="100">P</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[677,766,448,474]" italics="true" pageId="99" pageNumber="100">ochracea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 1.0× in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Crabo &amp; Lafontaine" authorityYear="2009" baseAuthorityName="Crabo &amp; Lafontaine" baseAuthorityYear="2009" box="[866,975,448,475]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Psammopolia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="99" pageNumber="100" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="insolens">
<emphasis box="[866,882,449,474]" italics="true" pageId="99" pageNumber="100">P</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[895,975,448,474]" italics="true" pageId="99" pageNumber="100">insolens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Crabo &amp; Lafontaine" authorityYear="2009" baseAuthorityName="Troubridge &amp; Mustelin" baseAuthorityYear="2009" box="[1030,1100,448,475]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Psammopolia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="99" pageNumber="100" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sala">
<emphasis box="[1030,1046,449,474]" italics="true" pageId="99" pageNumber="100">P</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[1060,1100,448,474]" italics="true" pageId="99" pageNumber="100">sala</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="99" pageNumber="100" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="99.[140,1108,167,580]" pageId="99" pageNumber="100">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[185,498,483,509]" pageId="99" pageNumber="100">
<emphasis box="[185,336,483,509]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="99" pageNumber="100" reason="1">Distribution</emphasis>
and biology.
</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authorityName="Crabo &amp; Lafontaine" authorityYear="2009" baseAuthorityName="Crabo &amp; Lafontaine" baseAuthorityYear="2009" box="[508,755,483,509]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Psammopolia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="99" pageNumber="100" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ochracea">
<emphasis box="[508,755,483,509]" italics="true" pageId="99" pageNumber="100">Psammopolia ochracea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is found in coastal 
<collectingRegion box="[993,1107,483,509]" country="United States of America" name="California" pageId="99" pageNumber="100">California</collectingRegion>
between San Francisco and Los Angeles. It flies in September and October. It occurs on sand beaches and is nocturnal.
</paragraph>
